description:
## Goal

Make the shared `MarkdownContent` module accept one Markdown base font size and derive the complete Markdown hierarchy proportionally, while preserving the exact 14px default appearance and every existing safety/interaction behavior.

This slice is intentionally independent from persistence and the Settings page. It creates one renderer interface used by Issue descriptions, comments, and the future live preview.

## Background and Evidence

`src/components/MarkdownContent.tsx` is the shared renderer for Issue descriptions and comments. It currently spreads fixed Tailwind sizes across paragraphs, headings, lists, blockquotes, tables, inline code, code blocks, and table headings. That makes a single preference impossible to apply consistently and risks partial scaling if callers style only the outer paragraph.

Current 14px relationships include approximately:

- paragraphs, lists, blockquotes, table body, and h4: 14px;
- h1: 20px;
- h2: 18px;
- h3: 16px;
- inline code: 0.85em relative to surrounding text;
- fenced code block text: 12px;
- table header metadata text: 10px;
- body/list line height: 24px.

The user explicitly chose one control that scales prose, headings, and code together. The renderer therefore needs one base at its article seam, not independent prose/code settings.

## Renderer Interface

Extend `MarkdownContent` with an optional numeric base-size prop whose name includes units, for example `fontSizePx` or `baseFontSizePx`.

- Callers that omit it render the current 14px design.
- The app Settings integration supplies only validated whole numbers from 8 through 72.
- The renderer should not silently clamp an invalid caller value into a different preference. Keep validation at the App Settings module/interface and use ordinary defensive handling only if required by React/CSS safety.
- Apply the dynamic value at the outer Markdown article/module seam, preferably through an inline CSS custom property or equivalently inspectable style. Do not generate dynamic Tailwind class names that can be omitted from the build.

The interface should remain small: Markdown source, optional external-link opener, optional class name, and optional base font size. Do not add per-element size props.

## Proportional Typography Contract

At the 14px default, preserve current computed sizes. Express descendants relative to the Markdown base so all supported values scale predictably.

Reference ratios from the existing implementation:

| Element | Default | Ratio to 14px base |
|---|---:|---:|
| Paragraph/list/blockquote/table body/h4 | 14px | 1rem |
| h1 | 20px | 1.4286rem |
| h2 | 18px | 1.2857rem |
| h3 | 16px | 1.1429rem |
| Fenced code | 12px | 0.8571rem |
| Table header metadata | 10px | 0.7143rem |
| Inline code | about 11.9px inside 14px prose | 0.85em of its immediate text context |

The exact decimal representation may be simplified where computed output remains effectively equivalent. Requirements are more important than literal constants:

- headings scale from the Markdown base;
- inline code scales with its surrounding prose and does not double-compound;
- fenced code receives exactly one relative size, not a `pre` ratio multiplied again by a nested `code` ratio;
- lists, task-list labels, blockquotes, tables, and comments inherit the intended body scale;
- body/list line heights become unitless or otherwise proportional so 72px text does not keep a 24px line box and clip;
- heading/code line heights remain readable at both extremes;
- code blocks and tables retain horizontal overflow behavior rather than widening the app shell;
- existing fixed padding, borders, colors, margins, radii, and font-family choices stay unchanged unless a font-size-dependent clipping defect requires a narrowly justified adjustment.

Do not apply the preference to the Issue Detail title, section labels, metadata, author/date lines, dependency rows, sidebar, input controls, or Workspace UI.

## Safety and Existing Behavior to Preserve

The typography refactor must not alter the Markdown feature/security interface:

- `skipHtml` continues suppressing raw HTML;
- GFM tables, strikethrough, and disabled task-list checkboxes continue to render;
- only HTTP/HTTPS destinations use the external-link opener;
- non-HTTP links remain inert visible text;
- external links retain new-window and `noopener noreferrer` behavior;
- code blocks and inline code remain distinguishable;
- all existing colors, font families, checkbox state, and semantic roles remain intact.

The Settings preview must call this same module later. Do not create a preview variant, preview stylesheet, or second renderer in this slice.

## Accessibility and Layout

Changing text size is itself an accessibility feature, so the supported extremes must remain usable:

- text must not overlap or be vertically clipped at 8px or 72px;
- the Markdown article must wrap normal prose;
- long code and wide tables may scroll horizontally inside their existing containers rather than forcing the desktop window wider;
- disabled task-list controls remain aligned with scaled labels;
- no fixed-height Markdown containers may truncate enlarged content;
- browser zoom and the Markdown preference must compose rather than overriding one another.

This is font-size scaling, not a general responsive redesign. The page may naturally require more scrolling at large values.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] `MarkdownContent` accepts one optional pixel base-size prop and defaults to 14px.
- [ ] The base is applied at one inspectable outer article/module seam.
- [ ] At 14px, computed paragraph, heading, code, list, blockquote, and table typography matches the current design.
- [ ] Paragraphs, h1-h4, lists, task-list text, blockquotes, table body/header text, inline code, and fenced code scale from the base.
- [ ] Relevant line heights scale proportionally and do not clip at 8px or 72px.
- [ ] Nested Markdown elements do not accidentally compound relative font-size rules.
- [ ] Code blocks and tables preserve contained horizontal overflow at large sizes.
- [ ] Issue description and comment callers can receive the same value through the same renderer interface.
- [ ] Future Settings preview callers need no renderer-specific workaround.
- [ ] No non-Markdown UI changes size.
- [ ] Existing raw-HTML suppression, GFM, task-list, external-link, inert-link, and code behavior remains unchanged.

## Test Plan

Extend the existing React Testing Library/Vitest renderer tests rather than replacing them.

Required focused coverage:

- omitted prop exposes 14px at the outer article;
- explicit 8, 14, a representative middle value such as 24, and 72 reach the article style;
- headings/code/table-header rules remain relative rather than fixed pixels;
- body/list line-height is proportional;
- a fenced code block does not receive a compounded nested code ratio;
- description and comment integration callers pass the same value;
- representative large Markdown does not introduce a fixed-height clipping class and retains overflow classes for code/table;
- all existing HTML suppression, GFM, checkbox, external-link, and inert-link tests remain green.

Prefer assertions on the stable module interface and class/style contract that the browser uses. Do not add brittle screenshots for ratio arithmetic; real computed style is covered again in desktop acceptance.

## Likely Files

- `src/components/MarkdownContent.tsx`;
- `src/components/MarkdownContent.test.tsx`;
- Issue Detail integration tests or props near `src/issues/IssueExplorer.tsx` only as needed to prove both description/comment call sites accept the value.

Do not manually edit generated RPC bindings and do not add storage/frontend settings state here.

## Verification

- focused Markdown renderer tests;
- existing Issue Detail/Markdown tests;
- `pnpm test`;
- TypeScript checking;
- Ultracite check/fix as appropriate;
- React Doctor regression scan because this changes shared React rendering;
- frontend build.

## Out of Scope

- persistence, TauRPC, Effect settings state, navigation, input, or preview page;
- font-family selection;
- separate code/prose sizes;
- general application zoom;
- changing Markdown syntax, plugins, sanitizer, or link protocols;
- visual snapshots for every integer in the supported range.

## Deviation Policy

Preserve the 14px appearance and safe renderer behavior as invariants. Stop and update this bead before changing the typography hierarchy, treating code as an independent preference, modifying Markdown parsing/link behavior, or scaling non-Markdown UI. A tiny spacing or alignment correction at 72px is acceptable only when a focused test demonstrates real clipping and the correction does not alter the 14px design.
